<TEXT>
leslie combs ii founder of spendthrift 
farm once one of the premier thoroughbred horse breeding 
operations died saturday at the university of kentucky medical 
center he was 88 
the hospital did not disclose the cause of death 
spendthrift started in 1936 grew from 126 acres to nearly 
6000 and once was the home of triple crown winners seattle slew 
and affirmed 
combs was a pioneer of modern racehorse syndication getting 20 
investors to put up 5000 each in the stallion beau pere in the 
1940s he later syndicated such outstanding horses as nashua 
majestic prince and raise a native 
combs was the first horseman to sell at yearling for 100000 
and the first to syndicate a stallion for 1 million 
his boldest move was taking spendthrift public in 1984 the farm 
filed for chapter 11 bankruptcy four years later and bankers 
agreed to forgive the farms 78 million debt horsemen henry 
hershey curtis green and william dupont iii bought the farms 
assets last year 
thomas meeker president of churchill downs inc in louisville 
called combs death a great loss to the thoroughbred industry 
hell be remembered as the master of spendthrift farm one of 
the greatest breeding operations in the world he said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

