<TEXT>
ronald e evans apollo 17 command module 
pilot on mans last trip to the moon died of a heart attack at his 
arizona home saturday he was 56 
the former astronaut died in his sleep and was found by his 
wife janet his motherinlaw marge pollom of sun city told the 
the topeka capitaljournal 
evans called his december 1972 flight to the moon in apollo 17 
the best experience i ever had in my life 
he left the astronaut program in 1977 to become an officer with 
western american energy corp in scottsdale ariz he was in demand 
as a public speaker and traveled widely 
evans was born in st francis kan and later lived in topeka 
kan 
he received a bachelors degree in electrical engineering from 
the university of kansas in 1956 where he enrolled in the rotc 
program and a masters degree in aeronautical engineering from the 
us naval postgraduate school in 1964 he was selected in 1963 for 
astronaut training and became an astronaut in 1966 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the rev w harold flowers a patriarch 
of the civil rights movement in arkansas and the oldest practicing 
black attorney in the state died saturday at a little rock 
hospital he was 78 and had been suffering from cancer 
his leadership his compassion and spiritual example touched 
so many lives gov bill clinton said 
he deserves the recognition in breaking the ice to enable 
blacks to participate on equal basis with other attorneys in 
representing their clients us district judge george howard jr 
said 
in one of his most celebrated trials flowers in 1947 defended 
two black men who had been charged with firstdegree murder in the 
deaths of two white men his motion to quash the entire jury on the 
grounds that there had been no black jurors in nearly 50 years led 
to the placement of 13 blacks on the prospective jurors panel 
with three eventually seated on the jury 
the defendants were found guilty of lesser charges marking the 
first time in arkansas that a black man had not gone to the 
electric chair upon conviction in the death of a white man 
flowers was ordained as a methodist minister in 1971 
in 1977 he was the first black named a special circuit judge 
for jefferson county in 1980 clinton appointed flowers as an 
associate justice of the state court of appeals 
a founder and former president of the national bar association 
he was inducted into the associations hall of fame in 1986 and was 
a past president of the american bar association and past state 
president of the national association for the advancement of 
colored people 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
retired thorougbred owner and breeder 
leslie combs ii founder of spendthrift farm and known as a pioneer 
of racehorse syndication died saturday at the university of 
kentucky medical center he was 88 
thomas meeker president of churchill downs inc in louisville 
called combs death a great loss to the thoroughbred industry 
hell be remembered as the master of spendthrift farm one of 
the greatest breeding operations in the world he said 
spendthrift started in 1936 once was renowned as a premier 
thoroughbred breeding operation growing from 126 acres to nearly 
6000 it once was the home of triple crown winners seattle slew 
and affirmed 
combs became known as the pioneer of modern racehorse 
syndication when he set a deal of 20 investors for 5000 each 
in the stallion beau pere in the 1940s he later syndicated such 
outstanding horses as nashua majestic prince and raise a native 
combs was the first horseman to sell at yearling for 100000 
and the first to syndicate a stallion for 1 million 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
arthur b singer a naturalist and painter whose 
watercolors of state birds were affixed to hundreds of thousands of 
letters mailed in the 1980s died of cancer saturday he was 72 
the stamp series bearing singers paintings is believed to have 
been the largestselling special issue in the history of us 
postage the postal service issued the stamps featuring the birds 
and flowers of the 50 states in 1982 
singer who graduated from the cooper union art school in new 
york in 1939 received its augustus st gaudens medal in 1962 after 
750 of his paintings appeared in birds of the world the first 
of many books he illustrated golden press issued a new edition of 
the book in 1983 
he received the hal borland award from the national audubon 
society in 1985 on the 200th anniversary of audubons birth 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
adolf pabst a mineralogy expert at the 
university of california at berkeley whose research was honored 
when a california silicate was named after him died tuesday at age 
90 
pabst taught in berkeley for 40 years and lectured around the 
world on his work in crystal deformation he received the roebling 
medal the highest honor bestowed by the mineralogical society of 
america which he served as president in 1951 
fellow scientists at berkeley named a california mineral 
pabstite in honor of his work in 1965 
