<TEXT>
hungarians voted sunday in a runoff 
election for the nations first freely elected multiparty 
legislature since 1947 and former communists were widely expected 
to serve only in the opposition 
no party was thought likely to win an outright majority in the 
polling which began at 6 am in most areas preliminary results 
were not expected before midnight six hours after the polls closed 
the first round of balloting almost two weeks ago left 261 of 
the 394 seats undecided in the national assembly 
but it gave two anticommunist parties a firm lead and relegated 
reform communists now running as the socialist party to fourth 
place with 10 percent of the vote 
the two frontrunners the conservative hungarian democratic 
forum and the liberalleftist league of free democrats have said 
they will not accept the socialists as coalition partners many 
still associate the socialist party with the hardline communists 
who ruled hungary for 43 years 
the two leading parties have been reluctant to comment publicly 
on the prospects of a coalition but the free democrats have said 
they would not rule out a joint government with the democratic 
forum 
a broad coalition is considered by many as the only government 
stable enough to make the hard decisions necessary to correct a 
stagnant economy while reining in a 20 billion national debt 
but a coalition with a consensus on economic policy could be 
difficult to forge since the leading parties have different views 
on the pacing and scope of economic reforms 
twentynine parties fielded candidates in the first round but 
only six reached the 4 percent minimum required for a seat in 
parliament 
candidates in the march 25 elections disputed 176 seats in 
direct balloting in electoral districts 
a clear winner emerged in only five of those districts they 
included socialist premier miklos nemeth a reformer who enjoys 
considerable popularity in the country 
an additional 210 seats were contested on the basis of the 
proportion of the vote parties received in the voting another 
eight seats are reserved for national minorities 
after the first round 120 seats were assigned on the basis of 
proportional voting the remaining 90 seats will be assigned on a 
proportional basis following sundays voting 
</TEXT>
