<TEXT>
greeks cast ballots in their third 
parliamentary election in ten months sunday amid projections that 
no party would win the outright majority needed to govern 
in athens long queues formed outside many polling stations when 
they opened at 701 am polls were scheduled to close at sunset 
or 754 pm 
more than 8 million voters chose among candidates from 27 
parties two coalitions and 16 independent groupings that stretched 
across the political spectrum voting is mandatory for greeks 
between 18 and 70 years of age 
only three parties were considered likely to attract significant 
numbers of voters the conservative new democracy the panhellenic 
socialist movement pasok and the communistled coalition of the 
left and progress 
but sundays election like those last june and november could 
end without a clear winner and again leave greece with a weak 
coalition unable to cope with a foundering economy and a resurgence 
of terrorism 
the outcome may also have bearing on the countrys four us 
military bases which could close in november unless a new 
agreement is reached with washington 
election officials said first results would be in hand two hours 
after the polls closed and definitive results by early tuesday 
in the two previous elections new democracy defeated pasok led 
by former premier andreas papandreou but fell short of winning an 
absolute majority in the 300member single house parliament 
opinion polls indicated new democracy led by 71yearold 
constantine mitsotakis was also the frontrunner in sundays voting 
but could again fail to achieve the necessary majority to govern 
alone 
such a result could lead to difficult negotiations between the 
three top parties over a ruling coalition and possibly another 
round of elections 
papandreou 71 has said he will attempt a progressive 
alliance with the communistled coalition to govern for the next 
four years 
last june new democracy teamed with the coalition its 
ideological opponents to govern from july to october the 
government was formed under the limited mandate of investigating 
corruption charges against papandreou and five of his ministers 
the parliament indicted papandreou on charges of ordering 
telephone tapping of political opponents and involvement in a 210 
million bank of crete embezzlement scandal the corruption charges 
helped bring down papandreous government but the charismatic 
leader continues to be a political force 
papandreou has denied the charges no date has been set for his 
trial 
in the november elections new democracy won 4619 percent of 
the vote for 148 seats pasok 4067 percent for 128 places and the 
coalition 1097 percent for 21 seats 
</TEXT>
