<TEXT>
slovenians voted sunday in the 
first free elections in yugoslavia since world war ii ending 45 
years of communist monopoly on power in the republic 
the 15 million registered voters will choose slovenias new 
president four members of the ruling collective presidency and 240 
members of the new multiparty parliament 
the 4130 polls in the republic opened at 7 am and were to 
close 12 hours later preliminary results are expected early monday 
and official results are due tuesday 
electoral laws require a runoff on april 22 between the top two 
votegetters if no presidential candidate receives more than 50 
percent 
four candidates are running for the republics presidency the 
principal election issues were whether or not slovenia should 
remain within the troubled federation and solutions for the 
inflationracked economy 
milan kucan a candidate of the reformist slovenian communist 
party which recently renamed itself the party for democratic 
renewal was ahead in the oppinion polls for the presidency 
his toughest opponent for the top post was former dissident joze 
pucnik a candidate of demos a coalition of five centerright 
parties 
preelections polls gave little chance to the other two 
presidential candidates 
pucnik a professor of philosophy spent seven years in 
slovenian prisons during the 1950s for his opposition to communism 
he was forced to emigrate to west germany from where he returned 
only last year after spending more than 20 years in exile 
slovenians are increasingly showing a desire to secede from 
yugoslavia because they are unhappy with the slow pace of 
democratic and other reforms in the rest of the country 
slovenias reformminded communists have moved quickly over the 
past three years to create a pluralistic system in the republic 
the reforms in slovenia have been implemented despite harsh 
criticism from serbia the largest yugoslav republic where 
communist leaders demand continued communist party dominance 
croatia the second largest republic is also scheduled to stage 
free parliamentary elections later in april 
despite allowing the formation of oposition parties communists 
in other four republics including serbia have not yet announced 
free elections 
yugoslavia is a loose federation of six republics and two 
autonomous provinces it is ruled by an eightman collective 
presidency 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

