supercomputer data to missile development 
the commerce department which takes the lead in granting or 
denying export licenses refused to comment but last week the 
department announced it had fined a west german company 800000 
for exporting nuclear material to india and several other countries 
in general the bush administration is easing controls over the 
export of supercomputers partly because of growing pressure from 
manufacturers stung by government budget cuts and partly because of 
a relaxation in technology exports to formerly communist 
governments 
the commerce department is pruning and streamlining the lists of 
hightech items banned for export to eastern europe and nato has 
been pressing the united states to speed up the process 
in addition the commerce department is redefining which 
supercomputers must receive special export licenses requiring a 
safeguard plan under the proposed definition countries buying 
supercomputers with a capability of up to 150 megaflops a measure 
of computing speed would not be required to adopt a safeguards 
plan the previous limit was 100 megaflops 
proponents of the sales argue that countries determined to 
produce nuclear weapons and ballistic missiles can do so without 
supercomputers especially since the new generation of desktop 
computers are so powerful they can compute as fast they note that 
supercomputers are put to many beneficial uses including weather 
predictions seismic analysis and medical and scientific research 
opponents argue that the fastcomputing machines make it much 
easier to design weapons especially because of their ability to 
simulate and analyze the effects of nuclear explosions and missile 
flights 
they also note that brazil india and israel have not signed the 
international nuclear nonproliferation treaty although all have 
nuclear capabilities or are near having them that means their 
nuclear facilities are not inspected by outsiders 
pressure from the industry is fierce especially in the face of 
sharp competition from japan the only other country that makes 
such machines us exports of supercomputers were valued at 400 
million in 1989 and are projected to double this year japans 1990 
exports are expected to reach 2 billion 
