<TEXT>
as the hubble space telescope awaits a ride 
into space scientists remain jittery about the many things that 
could go wrong with nasas costliest satellite from a fogged 
mirror to space junk 
its hitting us in our guts said ed weiler hubble program 
scientist at the agencys washington headquarters were all 
having dreams about this thing were reliving meetings on what 
could go wrong and were wondering did we make a mistake 
somewhere 
getting the 15 billion telescope ready to be placed in orbit 
by the shuttle discovery this week after seven years of delay 
has been one big pain in the rear but its going to be worth 
every minute every one of us spent on it he said 
because the unmanned telescope will peer farther into space than 
any other observatory we know we are going to discover things 
that are totally unexpected that our human imaginations cant even 
envision 
potential woes facing hubble include equipment failures 
contamination of its sensitive mirror and light detectors 
dependence for repairs on an overburdened shuttle fleet and 
sunspot activity that might drag the telescope from its proper 
orbit 
we have plenty of concerns and plenty of areas we know need 
improvement but we have no showstoppers said david r skillman 
a chief telescope engineer at goddard space flight center in 
maryland i fully expect this thing will be operating for 20 or 
30 years well beyond the planned 15year mission 
the national aeronautics and space administration plans to put 
hubble in orbit 380 miles above the earth higher than any shuttle 
has flown discovery is scheduled for launch tuesday 
but if one of discoverys three engines doesnt produce full 
power or fails completely after launch as happened to challenger 
in july 1985 the shuttle wouldnt reach an adequate altitude the 
astronauts would either bring the telescope back or put it in a 
lower orbit until a shuttle could tow it higher 
as long as hubble is deployed at least 326 miles above earth it 
can make some useful observations for a year before it needs a 
boost flight director william reeves said 
shuttle maintenance flights every three years will tow the 
telescope back up to 380 miles if its orbit decays because of 
sunspots the current solar cycle is the second most intense on 
record spewing solar wind that heats and inflates earths 
atmosphere increasing friction that can make satellites fall from 
orbit more quickly 
if the shuttle fleet were grounded for years by another tragedy 
like the challenger explosion the telescope could burn up in the 
atmosphere 
astronautastronomer steve hawley said vibration during 
discoverys ascent is unlikely to damage the telescopes mirror 
but if it sat on the pad for a long time you might worry about 
possible contamination 
thats because the shuttles cargo bay is not as clean as either 
the vacuum of space or the clean room where the telescope was 
readied for flight said mark johnston of the baltimorebased space 
telescope science institute which schedules use of telescope time 
installation of the hubble into the shuttles cargo bay was delayed 
briefly last month after insects invaded the clean room 
nasa officials believe they can deal with all conceivable 
troubles except the possibility the hubble might be obliterated by 
a speeding meteoroid or a hunk of junk from some previous space 
flight 
a study of air force space junk statistics concluded that there 
is a 1 percent chance that that a fragment large enough to destroy 
the telescope 4 inches wide would hit it during its 15year 
mission johnston said 
the telescope is aimed with internal gyroscopes but lacks 
thrusters to maneuver it away from an impending collision 
weiler disputed the 1 percent estimate as exaggerated so im 
not going to lose sleep over it 
because the launch has been delayed so long much of the 
telescopes equipment is aging and some might fail including 
electrical connections and moving parts such as camera shutters and 
filter wheels johnston said 
hubble is designed so that as parts fail other parts can be 
turned on to replace them skillman said 
if a malfunction seriously threatens the telescope nasa is 
committed to launching a shuttle within a year instead of waiting 
for a regular maintenance mission 
but if i were a hubble space telescope project guy i would 
always carry with me a lingering concern that when i need the 
support is it going to be available to me hawley said 
when shuttles approach on servicing missions thrust exhaust 
might fog hubbles mirror but skillman said that can be prevented 
with careful maneuvering 
while hubbles orbit makes it accessible for repairs it also 
leaves the telescope able to make observations only 35 percent of 
each day johnston said 
earth will block desired targets 40 percent of the time the 
telescope needs 10 percent of its time to locate and lock onto 
guide stars so it remains steady it is unusable 15 percent of 
the time when it passes east of brazil where orbiting radiation 
belts dip low enough to interfere with the telescopes electronics 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

