<TEXT>
there may be more varieties of matzoh now than 
when the israelites fled from egypt but the essential elements of 
the passover seder havent changed for thousands of years making 
it one of the oldest ritual sitdown dinners 
perhaps the reason the feast commemorating the exodus has 
survived so long is that its whole purpose is to pass on to 
generations of jews the story of their ancestors escape from 
slavery on monday at sundown jews all over the world will observe 
the tradition again 
one professor of jewish studies believes the gastronomic nature 
of the tradition may also have something to do with its longevity 
if you can hit them in the stomach it lasts said jon 
levenson a professor of jewish studies at harvard university 
elements of the family seder as it is practiced today date back 
some 1900 years to the time of the destruction of the second 
temple in jerusalem levenson said some parts of the tradition may 
date back roughly 3000 years 
some scholars believe jesus christs last supper was a seder 
thats unclear it certainly took place around passover time 
levenson said 
there are eastern religious meals that probably predate the 
jewish seder but documentation to trace when they began is 
sketchy according to religious scholars 
the meaning of the hebrew word for passover is debatable 
levenson said the popular explanation for the english word is that 
it describes the angel of death passing over the homes of jews 
who marked their doors with lambs blood according to exodus the 
angel of death was sent to slay the egyptians firstborn 
the modern explanation may be close to the original meaning of 
the word levenson believes the hebrew word pesach comes from a 
ritual dance 
the verb itself i think means jump leap levenson said 
it may very well indicate that the destroyer in exodus jumps 
over jewish homes 
the style of a modern seder varies with each family some allow 
for long discussions some are filled with song others adopt 
modern themes but the essential story and many of the props that 
go with it remain the same 
matzoh the flat bread that now comes in whole wheat egg and 
unsalted varieties symbolizes that the israelites fled so quickly 
from pharaoh they didnt have time to let their bread rise 
bitter herbs like horseradish recall the bitter taste of 
slavery and a sweet paste often made of apples raisins and nuts 
represents the mortar the jewish slaves used to build egyptian 
pyramids 
the seder story is built around questions from children usually 
posed by the youngest child at the table the responses are framed 
so that even the child who doesnt know how to ask a question can 
learn the exodus story 
the haggada is a book used to guide the meal traditional 
haggadot contain prayers blessings and appropriate readings some 
narratives are illustrated with pictures others are specially made 
for children and a feminist haggada even appeared several years 
ago references to the holocaust and to those lost in the nazi 
death camps are now common at many seder tables 
some families use the haggada as a starting point to lead into 
discussions of modernday problems 
marvin kalb a former television correspondent who now directs a 
center on media studies at harvard universitys kennedy school of 
government said talk at his familys seder table often turns to 
newsworthy topics 
were very political and we do talk about modern themes 
although we do go through the passover readings in a very 
traditional way kalb said 
kalb said he still recalls cleaning the house and changing the 
dishes in his boyhood home to prepare for passover he said the 
passover tradition has survived because it is built on an 
inherently interesting tale 
its a great story its a story of freedom kalb said 
author elie wiesel who has written extensively about his 
experiences as a holocaust survivor said his family sticks closely 
to the traditional haggada 
it is linked to the first holiday to the very beginning of 
history said wiesel who teaches at boston university we are 
always fascinated with beginnings after all i think its the 
first liberation story in history 
</TEXT>
