<TEXT>
at the state capitol education has lost 
its head commerce is shorthanded half of agriculture has 
disappeared entirely 
but its not because of budget cuts or governmental neglect 
its the damage caused by more than a century of wear and tear on 
12 allegorical statues in the state capitol 
in one of the final stages of a 38 million renovation of the 
capitol building the plaster of paris statues of greek women are 
being restored 
the six pairs of greekstyle statues on two stairway landings 
leading to the house balcony symbolize six pillars of connecticut 
culture education commerce force agriculture science and 
music 
on days when the general assembly is not in session sculptor 
john d leslie carefully shapes clay molds to recreate the hands 
heads and toes that have been chipped away by a centurys worth of 
passing tourists and lobbyists 
its a fascinating project he said theres no 
deterioration in the material itself its just that the statues 
have been banged and chipped over the years 
sculpted in 1876 by john quincy adams ward of new york the 
statues are actually the scale models that adams used to sculpt 12 
identical but larger marble statues that ring the outside of the 
capitol dome 
each statue depicts a greek woman holding an object showing her 
role agriculture holds an apple and a sheaf of wheat music strums 
on a lyre 
on the west landing commerce is missing a hand and a prankster 
once painted some of her toenails red she is nicknamed the 
goddess of basketball because she holds a small globe in one hand 
the head is gone on one of the two educations an agriculture 
was inadvertently knocked over by workers one day and taken by 
stretcher to the capitol basement for repair on both landings the 
barebreasted amazon who depicts force is missing her spear 
the restorer uses clay molds to make an exact match of the 
originals then casts a plaster of paris replacement directly onto 
the statue most of leslies work is done in hartford but he 
worked in his studio in guilford on a replacement head for 
education 
ive had to crawl inside mr wards head leslie said 
ive got to think like he did as best i can i dont want to 
improve his work thats not my job 
in most cases leslie can refer to the twin statue on the 
opposite landing to find the exact dimensions of the missing piece 
when both statues are missing the same part he uses binoculars to 
study the intact version of the statues on the outside of the 
capitol 
he will complete his 48000 contract by painting the statues a 
shade of tan identical to their original coat of paint 
leslie worked in a family foundry until he began restoring 
statues and ornamental work in historic buildings seven years ago 
his past projects include the statues of four dolphins in the 
courtyard of yales sterling library and work at the shubert 
theater in new haven 
his latest reconstruction which should keep him busy until 
june has given him a greater appreciation for wards work he said 
theres nothing by chance up there he said everyones 
dressed a certain way for a certain reason 
a contemporary of augustus saintgaudens ward is perhaps best 
known for his oftenphotographed statue of george washington on 
wall street in new york 
