<TEXT>
celebrated novelist mario vargas llosa won the 
first round of presidential elections sunday but he fell far short 
of the majority needed to avoid a runoff according to unofficial 
projections 
rebels trying to sabotage the elections attacked some polling 
stations in lima with dynamite sunday but no one was reported 
injured weekend guerrilla violence in peru killed at leaast 28 
people and wounded 44 authorities said 
the maoist shining path has assassinated six congressional 
candidates and killed or wounded dozens of other people in recent 
weeks aiming to disrupt the election 
vargas llosa 54 of the centerright democratic front 
coalition has run on a freemarket ticket he said the results 
showed voters had rejected leftist policies and the governing 
leftofcenter aprista party for its catastrophic five years in 
government 
the countrys political panorama has changed profoundly with 
this election he said 
the novelist captured 368 percent of the vote based on results 
from an exit poll by apoyo a market research firm 
apoyo said alberto fujimori the son of japanese immigrants was 
in second place in its projections with 267 percent fujimori is a 
political independent who was virtually unknown to peruvian voters 
as recently as a month ago 
peruvian public opinion projected 331 percent as vargas llosas 
final tally and 262 percent for fujimori 
apoyo one of perus most respected polling firms said its 
results were based on the initial 54 percent of its total 
interviews done nationwide it said that was a big enough sample to 
project a final vote 
the market research firm also said aprista party candidate luis 
alva castro had 132 percent of the votes in its projections it 
said henry pease candidate of the united left had 7 percent while 
alfonso barrantes candidate of the socialist left 4 percent 
the rest of the votes were spread among four minor party 
candidates and blank or nullified votes according to apoyo 
officials returns are not expected for weeks 
the peruvian public opinion poll had similar figures for the 
other candidates 
at a news conference vargas llosa proposed that he and fujimori 
meet to discuss ways to avoid a second election saving peru from 
the turmoil of two more months of campaigning 
fujimori arrived minutes later at the news conference and 
congratulated vargas llosa but at a later news conference he 
rejected any possibility of stepping aside to avoid a runoff 
i believe a second round is necessary to debate our 
proposals he said the verdict should be the publics 
during the campaign vargas llosa has sharply attacked the 
aprista party and the two leftist alliances he is unlikely to have 
their support in the runoff 
in contrast fujimori has run a conciliatory campaign without 
attacks he is believed to have support within the aprista party 
the left is not going to support the democratic front because 
of the polarization that has been generated in the country 
fujimori said in a news conference after polls closed at 5 pm 
the campaign has brought a surge in popularity for fujimori 
last week fujimori 51 rose into second place in voter surveys 
displacing alva castro 48 
the peruvian public opionion projections of the final vote also 
indicated the democratic front would win only 23 seats in the 
60seat senate and 63 seats in the 180seat chamber of deputies 
that would make it very difficult for vargas llosa 54 to 
impose the severe austerity measures he has pledged if he wins he 
says radical economic reforms are needed to revive perus moribund 
economy and turn peru into a modern nation free of the 
socialist policies he says have stiffled growth for two decades 
inflation is running at more than 2000 percent annually 
voters are choosing a president to replace populist alan garcia 
whose fiveyear term ends july 28 he is legally ineligible to 
serve a consecutive term 
during sundays voting soldiers armed with automatic weapons 
protected polling stations against terrorist attacks 
leftist guerrillas exploded sticks of dynamite near two polling 
stations early sunday in downtown lima and an outlying shantytown 
police said the explosions caused no damage and no one was injured 
the government said nearly 80000 policemen were on alert 
throughout the country more than 200000 army troops were 
providing security in the countrys mountainous emergency zones 
where guerrillas are most active 
on saturday police said maoist shining path guerrillas blew up 
municipal buildings and sacked stores killing 17 peasants and 
wounding 13 in the mountain village of santo thomas de pata about 
18 miles northwest of ayacucho 
army forces retailated sunday tracking down the rebels and 
killing six in a fierce firefight police said one soldier was 
also killed in the battle 
also sunday two members of the shining path were killed in the 
central andes when the bomb they were planting on a bridge 
exploded authorities said another rebel was badly wounded in the 
blast in the town of huasquis about 100 miles east of lima 
in lima where onethird of perus voters live police patrolled 
the streets in armored vehicles and diverted traffic around the 
capitals 15837 polling stations 
people entering voting stations were searched for weapons the 
government asked voters to go to the polls emptyhanded to 
facilitate searches 
fear of rebel attacks paralyzed bus traffic between towns in 
mountainous insurgency zones but election officials said voter 
turnout was heavy despite threats by the shining path guerrilla 
group to kill voters and candidates 
television stations showed lines of voters up to five blocks 
long in huancayo in the andes 120 miles east of lima huancayo a 
major trading center is a shining path stronghold 
in some areas of the country election officials suspended the 
requirement that voters dip their index fingers into indelible ink 
after casting ballots the guerrillas have killed highland peasants 
and cut off their hands as a warning not to vote 
voters leaving polling stations sunday morning in the 
workingclass neighborhood of la victoria expressed support mainly 
for fujimori and vargas llosa who put aside his writing two years 
ago to campaign for the presidency 
mariana pino de grecia a housewife said she voted for vargas 
llosa 
the country needs someone known internationally to attract 
aid fujimori is not known he doesnt have a plan of government 
and hes too new she said 
but taxi driver angel torres said he voted for fujimori 
lets see what fujimori can do he said the others are 
old politicians hes more honorable harderworking 
voting is required by law violators are subject to heavy 
penalties including a fine equivalent to half the monthly minimum 
wage of 45 
the maoist shining path guerrilla group launched its insurgency 
in may 1980 by burning ballot boxes near the highland city of 
ayacucho since then nearly 20000 people have been killed in 
political violence including rebels police soldiers and 
civilians 
</TEXT>
