<TEXT>
pepsico inc and the soviet union are expected 
to sign an agreement to trade pepsicola for ships and vodka which 
would be the largest deal between that country and a us 
corporation the new york times reported 
the deal is valued at more than 3 billion and is expected to be 
announced monday the times reported in monday editions 
the agreement would make pepsicola much more available in the 
soviet union while enabling pepsico to take out its profits not 
just in the form of stolichnaya vodka but in oceangoing freighters 
and tankers 
the agreement is being watched as an indicator of whether 
western companies can succeed in the soviet union the newspaper 
said 
the purchase nybased company became the first large us 
company to enter the soviet union in 1974 when it began trading 
pepsi for stolichnaya 
pepsico ships its softdrink syrup to the soviet union where it 
is made into cola and sold in bottles the vodka was sold through a 
third party in the united states 
the new deal calls for the soviet union to trade at least 10 
tankers with a total value of 300 million the times said 
the agreement would also allow pepisco to sell pepsi in plastic 
bottles and aluminium cans instead of just glass bottles and calls 
for increasing the number of bottling plants from 26 to 50 the 
newspaper said 
this deal is going to make the soviet union a very big 
business for us john swanhaus president of pepsicos wines and 
spirits subsidiary told the times 
pepsi sells in the soviet union for the equivalent of 75 cents 
for an 11ounce bottle 
</TEXT>
